Which of the following is NOT an Obligation of Licensees to the Public according to 2024-25 Model Rules, Section 240.15?
choices: Licensees shall be cognizant that their first and foremost responsibility is to safeguard the health, safety, and welfare of the public when performing services for clients and employers.
Licensees shall express a professional opinion publicly only when it is founded upon an adequate knowledge of the facts and a competent evaluation of the subject matter.
Licensees shall not knowingly provide false or incomplete information regarding an applicant in obtaining licensure.

Licensees shall issue no statements, criticisms, or arguments on engineering and surveying matters that are inspired or paid for by interested parties especially when they explicitly identify the interested parties on whose behalf they are speaking and reveal any interest they have in the matters.

You are a licensed professional engineer (PE) working for a consulting firm. A client requests that you sign and seal engineering drawings for a project you did not personally prepare or supervise. The drawings were prepared by a junior engineer who is not licensed, and you have not had the opportunity to thoroughly review the work due to time constraints. The client insists that your seal is needed urgently to meet a permitting deadline. What should you do, and why?
choices: Refuse to sign and seal the drawings until you have thoroughly reviewed and verified their accuracy and compliance with applicable codes and standards.
Delegate the review to another unlicensed engineer and then sign and seal the drawings based on their assurance.
Sign and seal the drawings immediately to meet the client’s deadline, trusting the junior engineer’s work.
Sign and seal the drawings but include a disclaimer that you did not prepare or review them.
